New Residential Development Absortion in Portugal

Portugal’s housing market continues to illustrate a structural imbalance between supply and demand, one that real estate investors cannot ignore.

According to recent data from Idealista, the number of newly built homes listed for sale in Portugal has more than doubled over the past five years, reaching nearly 21,000 units by the end of 2025. On the surface, this looks like strong supply growth.

Yet the reality is more nuanced: new supply is still materially below the country’s housing needs.

Demand continues to absorb new inventory quickly. By the third quarter of 2025, almost 25,000 newly built homes had already been sold, representing about 20% of all residential transactions, according to Instituto Nacional de Estatística.

From an investment perspective, the pricing dynamics are equally telling.

New homes are being sold at an average 40% premium compared to existing housing stock, with national asking prices averaging €4,165/m² in late 2025. In the most competitive markets, the gap is even more pronounced:

• Lisbon: €7,574/m²
• Porto: €4,236/m²
• Funchal: €4,833/m²

The reasons are structural and familiar to anyone active in development:
rising construction costs, labor shortages, expensive urban land, slow permitting processes, and a heavy tax burden.

Encouragingly, policy adjustments are beginning to emerge. The government has introduced measures including reducing VAT from 23% to 6% on new residential construction up to €660,000, alongside initiatives to accelerate urban licensing approvals.

Early indicators are positive. Nearly 39,000 housing units were licensed in 2025, the highest level in five years.

However, from a capital markets perspective, the key takeaway remains clear:

Portugal’s housing shortage is not simply a cyclical issue, it is structural. And while new development activity is increasing, supply will likely take years to catch up with demand.

For investors and developers, this reinforces a central thesis:
markets with persistent supply constraints tend to generate long-term pricing resilience and strong absorption dynamics.

In other words, demand in Portugal’s residential market is not just strong, it is structurally embedded.